The energy associated with the forces acting upon charged particles and their subsequent movement is a fundamental concept, often described as [electrical energy](/Energy). This energy is transferred when [electric charges](/Electric_charge) traverse between locations possessing different [electric potentials](/Electric_potential), essentially moving across a [potential difference](/Voltage). As these charges either gain or lose electric potential, work is performed, leading to a transformation in the energy state of a particular system. The precise quantity of this work, measured in [joules](/Joule), is determined by multiplying the magnitude of the charge that has been displaced, expressed in [coulombs](/Coulomb), by the potential difference it has crossed, quantified in [volts](/Volt). &#91;1&#93;

In practical terms, the sale of electrical energy is predominantly conducted using the [kilowatt hour](/Kilowatt_hour) as the unit of measurement. One kilowatt hour, equivalent to 3.6 megajoules, represents the product of power, measured in kilowatts, and the duration of operation in hours. The entities responsible for supplying electricity, known as electric utilities, meticulously track the energy delivered to their customers through devices called [electricity meters](/Electricity_meter), which maintain a continuous record of consumption.

A common manifestation of converting electrical energy into a more tangible form is observed in [electric heating](/Electric_heating), where it is transformed into [thermal energy](/Thermal_energy). The most straightforward and widely employed method for electric heating involves utilizing [electrical resistance](/Electrical_resistance) to facilitate this energy conversion. However, electrical energy can be harnessed through various other mechanisms. When electric charges are in motion, forming an electric current, and pass through a heating element subjected to a potential difference across its extremities, energy is transferred from the charges to the element. This process augments the element's temperature and its stored thermal energy, as the moving charges dissipate their potential energy.

### Electricity Generation

The intricate process of generating electrical energy from diverse [forms of energy](/Forms_of_energy) is known as electricity generation. The foundational principles underpinning this phenomenon were meticulously unveiled during the 1820s and early 1830s by the distinguished British scientist [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday). His pioneering method, which remains the bedrock of modern electricity generation, involves inducing an electric current through the dynamic interaction of a conductive loop, such as a [disc of copper](/Homopolar_generator), with the magnetic field generated between the poles of a [magnet](/Magnet). &#91;2&#93;

For the vast network of electrical utilities, this generation process represents the initial crucial phase in the comprehensive delivery of electricity to end-users. Subsequent stages, including electricity [transmission](/Electric_power_transmission), its subsequent [distribution](/Electric_power_distribution), and the sophisticated methods of electrical energy storage and retrieval, such as those employed in [pumped-storage](/Pumped-storage_hydroelectricity) systems, are typically managed by the specialized [electric power industry](/Electric_power_industry). &#91;3&#93;

The predominant method for generating electricity involves large-scale facilities known as [power stations](/Power_station). Within these stations, electromechanical [generators](/Electrical_generator) are employed, primarily propelled by [heat engines](/Heat_engine). These heat engines are fueled by the chemical energy released during [combustion](/Combustion) or the energy liberated through [nuclear fission](/Nuclear_fission). Alternative means of driving these generators capitalize on the [kinetic energy](/Kinetic_energy) inherent in moving natural forces, such as flowing water or wind. Beyond these established technologies, a diverse array of other methods are actively utilized and continuously developed for electricity generation, including solar [photovoltaics](/Photovoltaics), which directly convert sunlight into electricity, and [geothermal power](/Geothermal_power), which harnesses the Earth's internal heat.

